tions (including national phase applications) which were filed in Israel before 12 July 2012 will be published gradually over the next 12 months, after a period of at least 18 months from their earliest priority date has elapsed.\n\nThe Israel Patent Office will notify the public which patent applications are available online starting with Patent Journal 08/2012.\n\nFor online review of published applications you may check the Patent Journal, starting 30 August 2012, at: http://www.justice.gov.il/MOJHeb/RashamHaptentim/Yoman/2012/ , where a link will be available for each application or go directly to http://www.ilpatsearch.justice.gov.il/UI to search the Israel Patent Office database.', 'תיקונים לחוק הפטנטים בישראל | Amendments to the Israeli patent law', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '661-revision', '', '', '2013-10-16 11:30:21', '2013-10-16 11:30:21', '', 661, 'http://ipatent.co.il/?p=662', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(663, 2, '2012-08-01 11:31:02', '2012-08-01 11:31:02', 'Ehrlich &amp; Fenster Offers New Service for Facilitating the Formation, Deposition, Maintenance and Enforcement of Trade Secrets.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTrade secrets are a common and powerful form of intellectual property, sometimes the most valued asset of the company. Businesses must be particularly careful when dealing with trade secrets because, unlike the case with patents or trademarks, failure to maintain the confidentiality required for trade secret protection can result in a complete loss of rights.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nExamples of trade secrets include, inter alia, technical information, formulas, germlines, germplasms, reproductive materials, genetic materials, databases, methods, processes, know-how, tolerances, computer programs, source codes, laboratory and research data, designs, improvements, product plans, SOPs and the like.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo be a trade secret, the subject information must not be generally known to the public or to persons outside of the company. The information must be sufficiently secret to confer an actual or potential economic or business advantage or benefit upon one who possesses the information.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn today’s increasingly competitive business climate, the need to protect proprietary technological and business information is at an all-time high. In some areas, it may be prudent to avail oneself to possibly more effective trade secret protection as opposed to patent issuance, under which it may take years to obtain protection.\r\n\r\nBusinesses must understand the costs and benefits of different strategies for protecting intellectual property. Some forms of protection, including patent protection and trade secret protection, overlap. Knowing when to protect valuable information as a trade secret and when to protect it through patent procurement is vital to managing and optimizing such assets. Our patent attorneys are experienced in the relative strengths and weaknesses of patent versus trade secret protection that can help determine whether to maintain an invention as a trade secret, seek a patent or maintain a portion thereof as a trade secret, while securing patent protection to the remainder portions.\r\n\r\nEhrlich &amp; Fenster works with its clients to establish appropriate procedures to secure their sensitive information. When we encounter an invention or development for which the best IP protection is a trade secret we counsel our clients how to effectively protect the trade secret and to nevertheless generate value for the company.\r\n\r\nEhrlich &amp; Fenster now offers a service that includes:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n1. Identifying the trade secret;\r\n\r\n2. Integrating the secret in the IP portfolio of the client;\r\n\r\n3. Documenting the trade secret;\r\n\r\n4. Trade secret depository;\r\n\r\n5. Creating a reminder system for monitoring updates of the trade secret;\r\n\r\n6. When needed, updating the trade secret on a periodic basis;\r\n\r\n7. Guiding the client how to protect the secret;\r\n\r\n8. Assisting in protecting the secret;\r\n\r\n9. Forming a legal situation whereby breach of confidentiality will more likely be enforceable against a third party; and\r\n\r\n10. Guide the client on the appropriate method of disclosure of the trade secret during a due diligence process.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen you believe that protecting a matter as a trade secret may be advisable, please contact Ehrlich &amp; Fenster for a strategic meeting between your company and us.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Trade Secrets', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'trade-secrets', '', '', '2013-10-16 11:32:40', '2013-10-16 11:32:40', '', 0, 'http://ipatent.co.il/?p=663', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(664, 2, '2013-10-16 11:32:04', '2013-10-16 11:32:04', 'Ehrlich &amp; Fenster Offers New Service for Facilitating the Formation, Deposition, Maintenance and Enforcement of Trade Secrets. Trade secrets are a common and powerful form of intellectual property, sometimes the most valued asset of the company. Businesses must be particularly careful when dealing with trade secrets because, unlike the case with patents or trademarks, failure to maintain the confidentiality required for trade secret protection can result in a complete loss of rights. Examples of trade secrets include, inter alia, technical information, formulas, germlines, germplasms, reproductive materials, genetic materials, databases, methods, processes, know-how, tolerances, computer programs, source codes, laboratory and research data, designs, improvements, product plans, SOPs and the like. To be a trade secret, the subject information must not be generally known to the public or to persons outside of the company. The information must be sufficiently secret to confer an actual or potential economic or business advantage or benefit upon one who possesses the information. In today’s increasingly competitive business climate, the need to protect proprietary technological and business information is at an all-time high. In some areas, it may be prudent to avail oneself to possibly more effective trade secret protection as opposed to patent issuance, under which it may take years to obtain protection. Businesses must understand the costs and benefits of different strategies for protecting intellectual property. Some forms of protection, including patent protection and trade secret protection, overlap. Knowing when to protect valuable information as a trade secret and when to protect it through patent procurement is vital to managing and optimizing such assets. Our patent attorneys are experienced in the relative strengths and weaknesses of patent versus trade secret protection that can help determine whether to maintain an invention as a trade secret, seek a patent or maintain a portion thereof as a trade secret, while securing patent protection to the remainder portions. Ehrlich &amp; Fenster works with its clients to establish appropriate procedures to secure their sensitive information. When we encounter an invention or development for which the best IP protection is a trade secret we counsel our clients how to effectively protect the trade secret and to nevertheless generate value for the company. Ehrlich &amp; Fenster now offers a service that includes: 1. Identifying the trade secret; 2. Integrating the secret in the IP portfolio of the client; 3. Documenting the trade secret; 4. Trade secret depository; 5. Creating a reminder system for monitoring updates of the trade secret; 6. When needed, updating the trade secret on a periodic basis; 7. Guiding the client how to protect the secret; 8. Assisting in protecting the secret; 9. Forming a legal situation whereby breach of confidentiality will more likely be enforceable against a third party; and 10. Guide the client on the appropriate method of disclosure of the trade secret during a due diligence process. When you believe that protecting a matter as a trade secret may be advisable, please contact Ehrlich &amp; Fenster for a strategic meeting between your company and us.', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '663-revision', '', '', '2013-10-16 11:32:04', '2013-10-16 11:32:04', '', 663, 'http://ipatent.co.il/?p=664', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
